text: hi I'm Molly and my culture shock story
today is about hiking fashion I love to
hike and I was really excited to come to
Seoul and hike bukhansan and Ciroc Sun
and just to have all these beautiful
mountains around me and to be able to go
whenever I wanted because back in
Chicago I can't always just go hiking
whenever I want I have to kind of plan
it and go and make a big deal out of it
so I was really excited to go hiking
here and the first time I went hiking I
wasn't actually looking at the mountains
and the trees I was looking at the
people because I was looking at that
they were wearing all their matching
outfits and they looked so professional
and put together and it's bright neon
colors with all these name-brand hiking
gear and I I actually felt really
underdressed like I had missed some kind
of message saying you need to look your
best when you go hiking and I was just
wearing I looked at I was just wearing
my old shorts my old t-shirt and my old
hiking shoes I had had for years and
years and it wasn't as enjoyable for me
to be hiking up this mountain feeling
like everyone was kind of looking at me
and what I was wearing and to me in my
opinion hiking should be something that
you go and do because you're outdoors
and it's a physical activity it's
exercise and you shouldn't be we're
worried about what you're wearing but
here it seems that everyone pre plans
this outfit and you have to look your
best so I would hope that Koreans are
actually really enjoying hiking and
maybe the hiking fashion is just a part
of why they like hiking but to me it's a
little overdone so I'm Molly and that's
my culture shock story bye
you
